<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hong Kong CPPCC Members Blame UK on Hong Kong Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803034794 Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0803034794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National News Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] Hong Kong members of the National Committee of the 
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC] who 
are to attend the Second Session of the Eighth CPPCC National 
Committee left Hong Kong for Beijing by plane at noon today. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified CPPCC member] I think 
everyone has now clearly seen that during the remaining time, it 
is impossible to place our hopes on the British side for 
cooperation for a smooth transition of power. 
  [Second unidentified CPPCC member] Now, the Hong Kong issue 
is not whether or not we want democracy. The process for 
democracy has been properly arranged by the Basic Law. It 
includes a method by which we can proceed in an orderly way and 
step by step. It can enable Hong Kong to develop properly and 
to prosper today, tomorrow, and in the future. The 
complications and the causes have all been created by the 
British side, which has ulterior motives. Therefore, the 
compatriots in Hong Kong and the people in China will not agree 
with them. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

