<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on CPPCC Second Plenary Session </TI></H3>
<H4>   Constitutional Revision Under Way </H4>
<F P=102> OW0803131894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1240 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 8 (XINHUA) -- The current session of 
China's top political consultative body is in the process of 
revising its constitution. 
  A constitutional amendment panel under the Eighth National 
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference (CPPCC) has submitted a revised CPPCC constitution 
(draft) to the CPPCC plenary session that opened here this 
afternoon. 
  The panel says in its explanation to the session that the 
revision aims to make the CPPCC constitution conform better to 
the latest amendments to the constitution of the People's 
Republic of China and to the tenets of the 14th National 
Congress of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC). 
  The panel notes that the revised constitution will highlight 
the theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, 
CPC's basic line of taking economic development as the central 
task and the multi-party cooperation system under CPC 
leadership. The constitutional revision is designed to improve 
CPPCC's status and role in the political life of China, it says. 
  According to the panel, since the major principles and basic 
framework of the 1982 constitution have remained correct, it has 
recommended only a necessary and partial revision. It suggests 
that issues which have a bearing on the work of the CPPCC but 
are beyond the limits of the CPPCC constitution be handled 
through state legislation and other channels. 
  According to the panel headed by CPPCC Chairman Li Ruihuan, 
the revised CPPCC constitution (draft) has been approved by the 
Standing Committee of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee and is 
being submitted to the general session for examination and 
adoption. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

