<H3> <TI>   Reportage on CPPCC Second Plenary Session </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputies Warned Against Leaking Reports </H4>
<F P=102> HK0803045594 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 8 
Mar 94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> HK0803045594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Chris Yeung in Beijing] </F>
  [Text] China has tightened control over the leaking of 
information on the annual plenary sessions of the NPC and CPPCC, 
which open today and on Thursday [10 March] respectively. 
Deputies said the move was another indication of the tense 
political atmosphere in Beijing. 
  Sources said the 2,000 deputies of the CPPCC had been warned 
not to divulge the contents of reports marked "confidential". 
These include the Government Work Report to be submitted by the 
premier, Li Peng, to the second plenum of the Eighth National 
People's Congress session. "It appears that the atmosphere is a 
bit more tense this year," a CPPCC delegate said. "Of course, 
there's nothing really sensitive in the work reports." But how 
the Chinese leadership saw the political situation was 
different, he said. 
  The communist regime tightened control over the media 
following the leaking of a work report by the Communist Party 
chief, Jiang Zemin, at a party plenum in 1992 -- days before it 
was scheduled to be delivered by Mr Jiang. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

