<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Views Steps in Eradicating Poverty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403163394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1527 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup": "China's Poverty Reduction Enters Crucial Stage"] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, March 4 (XINHUA) -- Following its success 
in helping 120 million Chinese escape from poverty since 1978, 
China's poverty reduction now enters the most arduous stage. 
  According to a plan announced by the Chinese Government 
earlier this week, China is determined to wipe out abject 
poverty by the year 2000, solving food and clothing shortages 
for its now-remaining 80 million poverty-stricken citizens. 
  The ambitious plan is significant in the history both of the 
Chinese people and mankind, for the rights to subsistence of 
1.18 billion Chinese, which make up a quarter of the world 
population, will soon have this fundamental human right secured. 
  Most of the 80 million people, about the same number as the 
whole German population, live in remote mountain regions, rocky 
regions, Loess plateau areas and remote deserts. Their lives 
are disastrously affected by acute shortage of water and poor 
public transport services, which make agricultural production 
difficult, not to mention industrial development. 
  The per capita share of water in the poor areas is between a 
16th and a 24th of the world's average. Electricity, education 
and transport services are hardly available to most of the areas. 
  Compared with the poverty eased among about 45 million poor 
people during the 1986-1992 period, the remaining poverty facing 
80 million Chinese is much more difficult to wipe out than the 
steps taken by China in 1978-1985. 
  The population of the poor decreased from about 200 million 
in 1978 to 125 million in 1985, when China abolished the commune 
system and introduced the household contract responsibility 
system. The reform resulted in a sharp increase in grain output 
and farmers' incomes. 
  During the eight-year poverty-reduction drive since 1986, 
China earmarked about 30 billion yuan worth of grain, clothes 
and other consumer goods for poverty alleviation, and allocated 
about five billion yuan in aid or discount loans to help the 
poor areas. 
  For the next seven years, in comparison, China should do at 
least twice as much. It should help 11 million escape from 
poverty each year during the coming seven years, while, on 
average, only 6.4 million poor people did so each year in the 
past seven, by getting enough food and clothes. 
  Despite the difficulty, China has many positive factors in 
its fight against poverty, such as the growing government 
investment, the priority given by the central and local 
governments to social and economic development in the poor 
areas, and support given by all walks of life and the 
international organizations. 
  A recent government decision stipulates that when preparing 
national and regional budgets, a set sum of money should be used 
for poverty reduction by the central and local financial 
departments. 
  To beef up the poverty reduction drive, the central 
government also made a decision to increase its investment in 
the "work for food program" by one billion yuan each year before 
the end of this century, and also extend one billion yuan 
discount loans to the poor areas. 
  The investment in the program would total four billion yuan 
in 1994 and 1995, respectively. 
  China's opening of its developing inland areas, particularly 
the border areas, has promoted local businesses and benefited 
from their trade with their neighboring countries or other areas. 
  The booming Chinese economy also contributed greatly to 
poverty alleviation, offering many jobs to surplus laborers in 
the poor area. 
  About 10 million surplus farmers in China's most populous 
Sichuan Province were employed last year by businesses in and 
outside the province, who earned a total of 10 billion yuan. 
  Past practice shows that if a laborer from a poor rural 
family is hired by a business, the money earned by the laborer 
will enable the whole of his poor family to get enough food and 
clothes. 
  In addition, the poor areas, which are rich in resources, 
will earn much more money as China is reforming its commodity 
circulation and pricing systems, including a gradual lifting of 
its control over prices of raw materials and primary goods. 
  All these factors, together with other efforts, such as 
making water, power, education, public health and transport 
services available to the poor, will certainly ensure the 
realization of the plan to wipe out abject poverty in China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2324 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi045_k_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-045 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders' Activities 23 Feb-3 Mar 94 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403160894 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403160894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] PRC media monitored by Okinawa Bureau 
carried the following reports on PRC leadership activities from 
23 February to 3 March 1994. The source is noted in parentheses 
after each report. 
  Zou Jiahua Meets Sino-Foreign Petrochemical Project Partners 
-- Zou Jiahua, vice premier of the State Council, recently met 
with several directors of a foreign company which is China's 
partner in a Sino-foreign joint-venture petrochemical industrial 
project in the South China Sea. The total investments of the 
project will be about $5 billion. The plant is in Guangdong's 
Huizhou and expected to begin operations in 1998. (Beijing 
Central Television Program One Network in Mandarin 1400 GMT 23 
Feb 94) 
  Jiang Zemin, Others Inscribe for Chinese Academy of Social 
Sciences -- The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences [CASS] closed 
its conference on work for 1994 on 25 February. Jiang Zemin and 
Li Peng have written inscriptions for CASS, encouraging it to 
continue reform. Jiang Zemin's inscription reads: "Intensify 
study, sum up experiences, and persist in integrating theory 
with reality to build the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences 
into a staunch position of Marxism." Li Peng's message reads: 
"Make the study of theory on socialism with Chinese 
characteristics your lofty mission." Ding Guangen called CASS 
and said: "I hope CASS will firmly take Comrade Deng Xiaoping's 
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics and 
the party's basic line as guidance, comprehensively follow the 
guidelines of the 14th CPC Congress and the Third Plenary 
Session of the 14th CPC Central Committee, emphasize the 
important task of `arming the people with scientific theory,' 
emancipate their minds, seek truth from facts, take the actual 
situation into consideration, make the focal points stand out, 
and intensify study in the theory of building socialism with 
Chinese characteristics as well as in important issues in the 
field of social sciences to better serve reform, opening up, and 
the modernization drive." Li Tieying said in his letter: "It is 
clear that China is now making greater efforts in reforming its 
economic and political systems and is stepping up the pace of 
modernization. Under the new situation, our tasks are very 
arduous and we are bound to meet a great deal of new problems. 
There are no existing experiences and answers ready for 
resolving these problems; we need to study and search them. The 
CPC, the state, and the people have placed great hopes on social 
sciences workers in this regard. We should firmly seize this 
historic opportunity; uphold Marxism as our guidance; better 
serve reform, opening up, and the construction of spiritual and 
material civilization; and serve as a good adviser and assistant 
to the CPC Central Committee and the State Council." Zhu Rongji 
also wrote to CASS. (Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 
0830 GMT 25 Feb 94) 
  Qiao Shi Meets Painter Cui Zifan -- On the morning of 25 
February, Qiao Shi, member of the Standing Committee of the CPC 
Central Committee Political Bureau and chairman of the National 
People's Congress Standing Committee, met with Beijing painter 
Cui Zifan, who donated 122 works to the China Art Gallery. Qiao 
Shi praised him, saying: "Your deeds have displayed and set a 
good example of the spirit of selflessness and dedication." 
(Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1110 GMT 25 Feb 94) 
  Zou Jiahua Attends Sino-German Agreement-signing Ceremony -- 
Zou Jiahua, vice premier of the State Council, attended an 
agreement- signing ceremony on 25 February held by the China 
National Technical Import and Export Corporation and a German 
company. Two boilers worth some $140 million will be imported 
from Germany for the Tianjin Huaneng Yang Liuqing Electric Power 
Plant. (Beijing Central Television Program One Network in 
Mandarin 1100 GMT 26 Feb 94) 
  Wu Bangguo Inscribes Name of TV Station-- A spring festival 
theatrical performance marked the inauguration of the Shanghai 
Educational Television Station on 27 February. Wu Bangguo, 
member of the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau and 
secretary of the Shanghai Municipal CPC Committee, inscribed the 
name of the station. Zhu Kaixuan, minister of the State 
Education Commission, delivered televised congratulatory 
message. Chen Zhili, deputy secretary of the municipal party 
committee, spoke at the opening ceremony. (Shanghai People's 
Radio Network In Mandarin 2300 GMT 27 Feb 94) 
  Liu Huaqing, Zou Jiahua Greet Opening of National 
Electronics 
Industry Work Conference -- Liu Huaqing, vice chairman of the 
Central Military Commission and Vice Premier Zou Jiahua sent 
greetings and congratulatory messages to the opening of the 
national electronics industry work conference on 28 February. 
"In his message, Liu Huaqing called on the electronics industry 
to strengthen scientific research and development, properly 
organize experimental systems and production, strive to achieve 
advanced international standards, and continue to provide 
advanced technological equipment to the various sectors of the 
national economy and the People's Liberation Army." In his 
congratulatory letter, Zou Jiahua urged the electronics industry 
to popularize electronics technology, reform traditional 
industry, constantly develop new products, pay attention to 
establishing various economic information systems, and strive to 
promote national economic development. (Beijing XINHUA Domestic 
Service in Chinese 0751 GMT 28 February 94) 
  Lu Rongjing, Fu Xishou Meet Sanyo Delegation -- Lu Rongjing, 
secretary of the Anhui Provincial CPC Committee, and Governor Fu 
Xishou separately met a delegation from the Sanyo Electric 
Company Limited led by President Yasuaki Takano on 27 February. 
Lu Rongji praised the far-sightedness shown by the Sanyo 
Electric Company in entering a joint venture with the Hefei 
Washing Machine General Company. Fu Xishou predicted broad 
prospects in store for the joint venture and wished it every 
success. (Hefei Anhui People's Radio Network in Mandarin 1100 
GMT 28 Feb 94) 
  Chen Xitong Thanks Retired Cadre for Waste-Cutting 
Suggestions -- Chen Xitong, secretary of the Beijing Municipal 
CPC Committee, recently expressed his appreciation to retired 
military cadre Lu Lian for writing a letter to him, putting 
forward several good suggestions for cutting waste while 
receiving retired cadres and for avoiding extravagance while 
conducting inaugurations and similiar ceremonies. (Beijing 
XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1319 GMT 28 February 94) 
  Li Peng, Liu Huaqing Inscribe for Dictionary -- A 
"Dictionary 
on Chinese Heroes and Martyrs" was jointly published by the 
Ministry of Civil Affairs and the Heilongjiang People's 
Publishing House recently. Premier Li Peng and Liu Huaqing, 
vice chairman of the Central Military Commission, wrote 
inscriptions for the dictionary, affirming the ideological and 
social significance and the practical value of the dictionary. 
(Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service 0809 GMT 1 Mar 93) 
  Chen Muhua, Luo Gan Present Awards to Outstanding Women -- 
The central government organs held a meeting to commend 10 
outstanding women, 100 women pacesetters, and 10 advanced units 
at Zhongnanhai on 1 March. These individuals and units were 
nominated by 95 departments under various state organs. Chen 
Muhua, vice chairman of the Standing Committee of the National 
People's Congress and president of the All-China Women's 
Federation, and Luo Gan, secretary of the Work Committee for 
Central Government Organs, attended the meeting and presented 
prizes and certificates to the advanced women and units. 
(Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0821 GMT 1 Mar 94) 
  Chen Junsheng Addresses Commendation Meeting on Greening -- 
On 1 March, the Beijing Municipality held a meeting at the Great 
Hall of the People to commend 606 advanced units and 1,048 
advanced individuals in Beijing for their greening efforts. 
Chen Junsheng, state councillor and chairman of the National 
Greening Committee, spoke at the meeting. He highly appraised 
the greening and beautification work in the capital and called 
for efforts to meet several new demands so as to do a better job 
in greening. (Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0257 
GMT 2 Mar 94) 
  Ren Jianxing Watches Theatrical Performance -- On the 
evening of 1 March, the Central Committee for Comprehensive 
Management of Public Security and the Propaganda Department of 
the CPC Central Committee held a large-scale theatrical 
performance at the State Theatre to mark the third anniversary 
of the promulgation of the "Decision on Strengthening the 
Central Management of Public Order." Ren Jianxing and Zhang 
Siqing, chairman and vice chairman, respectively, of the Central 
Committee for Comprehensive Management of Public Security 
watched the performance. (Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in 
Chinese 0829 GMT 2 mAR 94) 
  Chen Xitong Interviewed on Efforts to Promote Education -- A 
station reporter recently interviewed Beijing Municipal Party 
Secretary Cheng Xitong on the municpality's efforts to promote 
education. Chen Xitong talked about the his experience in 
implementing educational policy. Recollecting his previous 
visit to a city school some years ago, he described two things 
there which had spurred him to immediate action -- the words he 
saw on a blackboard asking who would pity a teacher's hard life 
and that school committee members pointed an accusing figure at 
him at a meeting for not paying adequate attention to education. 
Thereupon he resolved to vigorously promote education, and 
proposed "every leader, every party standing committee member, 
every mayor and vice mayor and every district party secretary 
must make it a point to keep in touch with schools, including 
all universities, middle schools and primary schools, and do 
practical work for them." Over the past eight years, 10 solid 
tasks have been performed annually, and this has been found to 
be very effective. (Beijing Central Television Network Program 
One in Mandarin 1100 GMT 1 Mar 94) 
  Wu Bangguo, Huang Ju Plant Trees -- Shanghai Municipal Party 
Committee and government leaders were among the first batch of 
the tree planting volunteers in the municipality this year. Wu 
Bangguo, Huang Ju, Chen Zhili, Wang Liping, Xu Kuangdi, Xie 
Lijuan, Xia Keqiang, Jiang Yiren, Sha Lin and other municipal 
leaders, as well as cadres from municipal government organs took 
part in a tree- planting drive early in the morning of 3 March. 
Wu Bangguo spoke on the importance of collective efforts to 
plant trees. (Shanghai People's Radio Network in Mandarin 1000 
GMT 3 Mar 94) 

</TEXT>

