<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gansu Prefecture Sees Growth of Rural Industry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402012994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0109 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402012994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lanzhou, February 24 (XINHUA) -- Dingxi prefecture, 
one of the poorest areas in northwest China's Gansu Province, 
has experienced a fast growth of rural industry over the past 
years. 
  According to local officials, the prefecture now has 41,867 
rural and township enterprises which created one billion yuan of 
output value last year, accounting for more than half of the 
total rural output value. The rural and township enterprises 
contributed 33.82 million yuan to the local revenue in the past 
year. 
  For a long time, Dingxi had been so poor that about half of 
its rural population did not have enough to eat or wear. 
  Since 1983, local government, together with relevant local 
departments, has proceeded in accordance with local conditions 
and begun to adjust the production structure in rural areas. 
They have adopted measures to encourage local farmers to set up 
rural and township enterprises or be engaged in diversified 
economy without neglecting grain production. 
  As a result, rural and township enterprises engaged in 
engineering, transport, carpet-making and food-processing 
sectors have mushroomed in Dingxi prefecture. 
  At the same time, the prefecture has also worked out 
preferential policies to attract outside investment for 
development of local resources. 
  The quick development of rural industry has also created 
more 
job opportunities for surplus rural labor, effectively improving 
the living standards of local residents. 
  At present, 170,000 rural laborers, or about 12 percent of 
their total, have found jobs in local rural and township 
enterprises. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2347 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi045_t_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-045 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

