<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gansu Protection Program Increases Arable Land </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102052194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0342 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102052194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lanzhou, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Northwest China's 
Gansu Province has slightly increased its cultivated area over 
the past five years, a local government official said here today. 
  The gain comes from a consistent policy of protecting 
farmland and an active approach to reclaiming wasteland. 
  He said that since 1989 about 33,367 ha of farmland had been 
taken over for non-agriculture construction in the province, 
while 46,953 ha of wasteland had been reclaimed. 
  Though its per capita possession of farmland is 0.16 ha, 
about one third higher than the national average, expanding 
cities and towns had been nibbling away cultivated area by some 
20,000 ha -- almost a mid-sized county -- a year in the early 
1980s. 
  To arrest the decrease in its cultivated area, the 
provincial 
government issued a series of laws and policies, according to 
which, taking any land for construction purpose had to be 
approved by, and only by, the land administration. 
  The provincial government also ruled that performance in 
land 
administration would be an important aspect of assessing the 
work of local governments. 
  The more than 60 development areas of the province were 
subjected to a review, and those with scant investment were 
declassified, so that the land could be cultivated again. 
  Over the years, the province also uncovered 1,494 cases in 
which construction projects had gone ahead without proper 
approval for use of land. 
  Meanwhile, the province has been encouraging farmers to 
reclaim wild land. Newly-developed farmland is used by the 
reclaimer and is immune from agricultural tax for the first 
three years. 
  In another development, 57 counties in the province have 
completed the setting up of "farmland protection areas," a 
program aimed to subject to protection those farmlands that are 
considered essential to its grain production, the official added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2348 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi045_t_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-045 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

