<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wei Jingsheng's Application for Departure Approved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803092294 Beijing China Radio International in English to 
Western North America 0400 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0803092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing China Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "World News" program] </F>
  [Text] China says reports by foreign mass media about the 
detention of Chinese dissidents are groundless. The Chinese 
Ministry of Public Security made the statement on Monday [7 
March] after overseas news organizations carried lists of 
dissidents detained during the weekend. The ministry explained 
some of the dissidents listed are under investigation because 
they are suspected of inciting turmoil and disrupting social 
order. Others named have not been detained. 
  The dissident Wei Jingsheng, one of those named by the 
foreign media, has applied for permission to leave Beijing on a 
private matter. The ministry said his application has been 
approved. 

</TEXT>

