<F P=100> Military </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liu Huaqing Discusses Military Legislation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403203294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1035 
GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0403203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Central People's Broadcasting Station reporter Wang </F>
Shude (3769 2885 1795) and XINHUA reporter Zhou Zhifang (0719 
1807 2455); Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese at 1349 
GMT on 4 March transmits a service message placing an open-ended 
embargo on this item] 
  [Text] Beijing, 4 Mar (XINHUA) -- Liu Huaqing, member of 
the Standing Committee of the CPC Central Committee Political 
Bureau and vice chairman of the Central Military Commission, met 
all the delegates to the all-army legislative work meeting 
today; and so did Central Military Commission Vice Chairman 
Zhang Zhen and Central Military Commission members Zhang 
Wannian, Yu Yongbo and Fu Quanyou. Liu Huaqing said: The 
People's Liberation Army [PLA] has made great achievements in 
military legislation. The tasks of governing the state and 
managing the Army according to law remain very heavy in the days 
to come, and we should continue to make efforts. 
  The all-army legislative work meeting was held in Beijing on 
3 March with the approval of the Central Military Commission. 
It was the first all-army legislative work meeting in the PLA's 
history. The meeting seriously adhered to the party central 
committee's guidelines on strengthening legislative work, as 
well as the Central Military Commission's principle of managing 
the Army according to law. It concentrated on studying how to 
accelerate military legislation, create a new situation of 
military legislation, and use military laws in guiding, 
promoting and protecting defense construction and army building 
under the conditions of building a socialist market economic 
structure and stepping up army building in the new period. 
Present at the meeting were persons in charge of relevant 
departments under the PLA's three general departments and major 
units and the Armed Police Force headquarters. The comrades in 
charge of the legislative affairs departments of the party 
central committee, the National People's Congress, and the State 
Council attended and addressed the meeting. 
  China has paid great attention to military legislation in 
recent years. The Central Military Commission set up its 
legislative bureau in 1988 to strengthen its leadership over 
military legislation. So far, the National People's Congress 
and its Standing Committee have successively promulgated nine 
military laws and legal decisions, including the "Military 
Service Law" and the "Law on Protection of Military 
Installations." More than 100 military regulations and military 
administrative regulations have been enacted either by the 
Central Military Commission alone or by the Central Military 
Commission and the State Council jointly. More than 1,000 sets 
of military rules have been formulated and published by the 
three general departments and major PLA units. So, a more 
feasible military legal system has been preliminarily 
established, and the planning of military legislation has 
improved. Moreover, the PLA has made great efforts to supervise 
and inspect law enforcement and to register all military rules 
and regulations, and the efforts have promoted the 
implementation of military laws and upheld the unity and dignity 
of the legal system. The PLA has also made remarkable 
achievements in publicizing the law, carrying out legal 
education, training legal affairs cadres, and providing legal 
counsel, as well as in jurisprudential studies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

