<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   New-Generation Weather Satellite To Be Launched in Apr </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403221094 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0829 
GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0403221094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondents Liu Zhiqing (2692 1807 3237) and Yang </F>
Jiuwei (2799 0036 0251)] 
  [Text] Beijing, 3 Mar (XINHUA) -- Our country's 
new-generation meteorological satellite, "Fengyun-2," was 
recently transported to the Xichang satellite launching center, 
where it will be lifted into space on a "Long March-3" carrier 
rocket in April. 
  This stationary-orbit meteorological satellite, developed by 
the Chinese Research Institute of Space Technology, will be used 
primarily to collect information for the preparation of 
visible-light and infrared-light cloud charts and water 
distribution maps; to collect and transmit observation data 
compiled by meteorological, maritime, and hydrological 
departments; to disseminate extended digital cloud charts, 
low-resolution cloud charts, and weather maps for use by ground 
stations at home and abroad; and to provide observation data for 
use in satellite engineering and space environmental science 
research. 
  Compared to the two "Fengyun-1" satellites launched in 1988 
and 1990, the new-generation meteorological satellite 
"Fengyun-2" reportedly represents a breakthrough in terms of 
technical performance, scope of application, and service life. 
The satellite employs a number of advanced technologies, such 
as scanning radiometry, slender-body control technology, and 
apogee engine separation, marking the first time such 
technologies have been used domestically, and signalling a new 
stage in our country's space technology. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

