<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dam Sturgeon Rescue Holds Lessons for Three Gorges Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0703095794 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0850 GMT 
7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0703095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 7 (CNS) -- According to a survey by 
relevant research institutions, Chinese sturgeons have 
extricated themselves from a predicament as a result of the 
construction of the Gezhou Dam at the river's upper reaches, 
with the young sturgeons now appearing in many places at the 
river's lower reaches in Anhui, Jiangxi and Jiangsu Provinces 
and the Shanghai Municipality, indicating success of the 
comprehensive sturgeon rescue plan including artificial 
sturgeon-breeding and the sending back of young sturgeons into 
the river. The Chinese sturgeon, an important endangered 
aquatic animal protected by the Chinese Government, used spawn 
in the Jinsha River, a branch of the Yangzte at its upper 
reaches. [sentence as received] With the construction of the 
Gezhou Dam, this species of fish was greatly reduced in number 
since their way back upstream for spawning had been cut off by 
the dam. In order to protect this variety of fish, considered a 
precious "living fossil", the Chinese Sturgeon Research 
Institute succeeded in developing an artificial sturgeon 
reproduction programme in 1984 and since that time they have 
sent back 2.35 million young sturgeons into the river. A survey 
conducted in 1991 showed that the number of this fish in the 
river has nearly reached the level before the construction of 
the dam. 
  According to experts, the above success has offered 
beneficial experience for the protection of precious endangered 
species facing similar environmental problems with the 
construction of the three Gorges Project. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2365 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi046_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canada Not To Link Trade to Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803181794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1737 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dhaka March 8 (XINHUA) -- A senior Canadian 
official has pledged his country will strengthen exchanges with 
China in various fields. 
  Addressing a press conference tonight at the end of his 
three-day official visit to Bangladesh, Canadian Secretary of 
State for Asia-Pacific Raymond Chan said that Canada is not in 
favor of linking trade with the so-called "human rights" in 
China. 
  It will strengthen it's trade as well as political, social 
and cultural exchanges with China, Chan affirmed. 
  Replying to a question, Chan also said that "Asia-Pacific 
region is playing more and more important role in the world and 
is becoming a more important trade partner of Canada." 
  Canada has to be more aggressive to seek out more trading 
partners in the region, the secretary for state said, adding: 
"Canada will continue to be friends of Asians." 
  As regards water sharing dispute between India and 
Bangladesh 
as well as Kashmir issue, Chan noted that his country is in 
favor of resolving those issues through bilateral talks and 
negotiations. 
  The South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) 
is a good forum for resolving bilateral issues among SAARC 
member states, he stressed. 
  Chan described Canada-Bangladesh relations as "very good," 
saying the recent economic and political developments here "make 
us optimistic about Bangladesh" and Canada would continue with 
its assistance to this country. 
  Canada's development program for Bangladesh is its largest 
worldwide and Canada is one of the major contributors to 
development assistance here. Approximately 2 billion Canadian 
dollars (about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars) has been provided to 
Bangladesh since its independence in 1971. 
  Chan arrived here on March 6. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

