<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng, Netherlands' Foreign Minister Hold Talks 8 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803140194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1321 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 8 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng met here this afternoon with visiting Dutch Minister of 
Foreign Affairs Pieter Kooijmans, saying that China attaches 
much importance to developing friendship and cooperation with 
the Netherlands. 
  Li said that the Netherlands was one of the earliest Western 
European countries to acknowledge the independence of the 
People's Republic of China. 
  He noted that there are no conflicts of fundamental 
interests 
between China and the Netherlands. 
  He said that the Netherlands is China's fifth largest trade 
partner in Western Europe and the two countries are cooperating 
in a wide range of areas including electronics, shipbuilding, 
petrochemicals, water conservancy and agriculture. 
  Li expressed the hope that the two sides will make fast 
progress in the talks on some large cooperation projects now 
underway. 
  China is a big market, Li said, and it offers many new 
cooperation opportunities to Western European countries 
including the Netherlands and the momentum of development in 
trade and cooperation between the two countries should continue. 
  Kooijmans said that Sino-Dutch economic and trade relations 
have been strengthened and the prospect for such cooperation is 
broad. 
  He noted that while meeting with the Chinese foreign 
minister 
and foreign trade minister, he expressed the sincerity of the 
Dutch side to further develop bilateral relations. 
  This afternoon, Minister of Justice Xiao Yang and Minister 
of 
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi met with Kooijmans 
on separate occasions. 
  Kooijmans and his party will end their China visit tomorrow 
morning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

