<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangsu Encourages `Scientific Farming' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703080794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0652 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703080794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nanjing, March 7 (XINHUA) -- Scientific farming in 
east China's Jiangsu Province has paid off. 
  A survey shows that farmers obtained an additional 2.43 
billion yuan from growing new varieties of grain and cotton on 
eight million hectares of farmland, averaging 240 yuan per 
household over the past three years. 
  Jiangsu began to encourage farmers in 1990 to undertake 
scientific farming in line with the market economy. 
  The province now has 12 comprehensive experimental farm 
centers, 324 townships and more than 2,000 villages doing 
pioneer work in the application of agro-science, and 150,000 
households specializing in scientific farming. 
  These organizations and households have formed a network to 
popularize agro-science. 
  While encouraging scientists to go to the rural areas to 
help 
farmers boost production, Jiangsu has paid attention to 
importing advanced technology for growing grapes and apples and 
cultivating rice. 

</TEXT>

