<H3> <TI>   High-Tech Boosts Industries in Zhejiang </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803022894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0213 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hangzhou, March 8 (XINHUA) -- East China's Zhejiang 
Province, the country's leading silk producer and exporter, has 
recovered from a slump by updating its technologies and 
retooling equipment. 
  The silk industry, like other traditional manufacturing 
sectors in Zhejiang and elsewhere in China, has been enlivened 
through input of new and high technology. 
  Since the beginning of the 1990s, Zhejiang has focused on 
the 
development of industries that concentrate on high technology 
and are capital intensive, and yield high added value. 
  High-tech development zones have been set up in this 
provincial capital, the port city of Ningbo and Wenzhou, where 
private enterprise thrives. 
  The machinery, chemicals, construction materials, textiles 
and light industry sectors have achieved better product quality 
and lower costs through the introduction of advanced technology. 
  According to Chang Jinming, deputy director of the 
provincial 
science and technology commission, as a province rich in labor 
but short on energy, resources and transportation, the only way 
for Zhejiang to gain a competitive edge in a market economy is 
to bring labor resources and technology into full play. 

</TEXT>

