<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Committee Nullifies Shenzhen Share Trading Act </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403134694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1314 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 4 (XINHUA) -- China Securities 
Regulatory Committee (CSRC), the country's top securities 
watchdog, has nullified a recent decision of the Shenzhen 
securities authorities. 
  The Shenzhen decision would have allowed trading in 1994 
bonus shares issued by former wholly state-owned enterprises six 
months after they were issued. 
  This is allowed for individual shareholders, but not for the 
50 percent of shares held by the enterprise on behalf of the 
state, nor for the 30 percent of the shares which may have been 
bought by other enterprises. 
  "Trading of state shares is an important issue concerning 
the 
readjustment of the government securities policy," said Zhu Li, 
the CSRC spokesman. 
  "Local securities offices or stock exchanges have no right 
to 
make any decision disregarding present relevant government 
rules." 
  So far, trading in shares other than those held by 
individuals is banned because it involves aspects of transfer of 
national property rights. 
  Zhu said that the CSRC had not been notified of the decision 
by Shenzhen securities office until the Beijing body read it 
today in a Shanghai newspaper. 
  But he said that the issue of allowing trading in those 
shares was now under heated discussion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

