<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Telecommunications Business Expands in Hainan Province </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703014494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0052 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703014494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Haikou, March 7 (XINHUA) -- Hainan Province in 
south China has poured more than one billion yuan into improving 
its telecommunications service during the past six years. 
  The installed capacity of urban telephones has reached more 
than 200,000 lines, eight times that of 1988, when setting up 
the province, as well as designating it as the largest special 
economic zone in China, was approved by the State Council. 
  The capital city of Haikou now has 27 telephones for every 
100 people, ranking among the top of China's provincial capital 
cities. 
  At present, automatic telephone service has been put into 
operation at or above the country town level. The province is 
thus on line with more than 1,400 cities at home and 195 
countries and regions in the world. 
  Various advanced communications facilities related to 
digital 
micro-wave, optical fiber, satellite, program-control, mobile 
and paging functions are in service in the province. 
  During the six-year period, the capacity of switchboards in 
the province's rural areas increased by 90 percent. 

</TEXT>

