<H3> <TI>   Hunan Province Strengthens Infrastructure Industry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0603013094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0116 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0603013094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Changsha, March 6 (XINHUA) -- Central China's Hunan 
Province, a major agricultural province of the country, has 
given priority to construction of infrastructure projects, 
aiming to improve its investment environment. 
  The province invested 86.2 percent of its funds in energy, 
transport, telecommunications, water conservancy and raw 
material industries in 1993. 
  By the end of last year, the province invested 5.762 billion 
yuan (about 700 million U.S. dollars) in key infrastructure 
projects, 2.3 times more than in 1992. 
  Construction of some projects has been completed and they 
have gone into operation, including Dayong Airport, three 
telecommunication projects and a bridge. 
  This year, the province plans to have 24 new projects, nine 
in transport, four in energy industry and two in 
telecommunications, with total investment of 14.5 billion yuan 
(about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars). 
  The province has made efforts to attract and raise funds for 
the work. It has issued bonds and stocks and imported foreign 
funds. 

</TEXT>

