<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hunan Boosts Export-Oriented Vegetable Production </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403081194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0650 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Changsha, March 4 (XINHUA) -- Central China's Hunan 
Province has boosted export-oriented vegetable production in the 
bid to increase farmers' income. 
  The province has taken full advantage of local geographic 
conditions, with two cities and a prefecture bordering on 
Guangdong Province and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, 
which are near to Hong Kong, Macao and Vietnam. 
  It has set up sales agencies in Guangdong and Guangxi to 
promote vegetable exports to Hong Kong, Macao and Vietnam. 
  Last year lingling prefecture exported over 200 million kg 
of 
garlic, sweet potatoes, tomatoes and radishes to Hong Kong and 
Vietnam, double the total of the previous year. 
  Tinned chillies from the Jianghua Autonomous County of the 
Yao nationality sells well on world markets. The product was 
the winner of a gold medal for new products at the fifth Chinese 
Commodity Fair. 
  Changsha, Yueyang and Hengyang cities exported 1,300 tons of 
tinned mushrooms last year, and more mushroom-growing villages 
and towns have emerged. 
  Guidong, Pingjiang and Lengshuijiang cities have succeeded 
in 
growing non-polluted vegetables for export. 
  Now the province has built up a number of export-oriented 
vegetable-growing bases with priority on developing more 
varieties and improving quality. 
  Meanwhile, advanced storage, processing and package 
techniques are being stressed. 

</TEXT>

