<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Affairs Council Limits Number of Foreign Workers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303083194 Taipei CNA in English 0716 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 3 (CNA) -- The Council of Labor 
Affairs (COLA), in a major shift of policy, has decided to limit 
the number of foreign laborers working on major construction 
projects to 65 percent of the total work force. 
  Cola Chairman Chao Shou-po said that the new regulation will 
go into effect March 16. 
  Previously, the COLA allowed public construction works to 
rely entirely on foreign laborers, but an easing of Taiwan's 
labor shortage has brought more domestic workers into the labor 
market. The average labor shortage rate in Taiwan was only 2.91 
percent in 1992, down from 5.16 percent in 1987. The labor 
shortage rate measures the percentage of unfilled positions in 
local firms. 
  Meanwhile, despite protests from workers' groups Wednesday 
[2 
March], COLA vice director of the labor-management relations 
department, Lai Ching-fong, reaffirmed COLA's decision to deport 
two Thai workers who the COLA said led a recent strike in 
central Taiwan. 
  The workers groups had requested that COLA overturn its 
decision to deport the two Thai workers. They also asked the 
COLA to provide interpreters for Filipino, Thai, Indonesian and 
Malaysian workers to give the workers a way of voicing their 
complaints. 
  Some 500 Thai workers at Taichung's Cheng Tai Yi 
Construction 
Co., went on strike last week, marking the first foreign 
workers' strike since the introduction of foreign labor to 
Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

