<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xiao Rong Questioned on Health of Deng Xiaoping </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903104894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0945 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0903104894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters Yu Yiguo (0358 1355 0948) and Zhang Huanli </F>
(1728 3562 0448)] 
  [Text] Tokyo, 9 Mar (XINHUA) -- Xiao Rong, the author of 
My Father Deng Xiaoping, said here on 8 March: 
Although Deng Xiaoping will be 90-years-old, he continues his 
workout, walking three km daily. 
  Xiao Rong made the above remark at a press conference at 
Tokyo Akasaka Prince Hotel. She arrived in Tokyo 7 March at the 
invitation of the Japanese bookstore Tokuma to launch the 
publication of her book in Japan. 
  At the 8 March news conference, Xiao Rong discussed the 
process of her writing the book and fielded questions from 
reporters. 
  On her father's view regarding China's present and future, 
she said: Deng Xiaoping believes China's decade-long policy of 
reform and opening up has laid the foundation. China is facing 
a new opportunity now, and China should seize it. He is fully 
confident about the future of China. 
  She said: "My father has a strong desire to go to Hong Kong 
after it returns to China in 1997. He said: 'In 1997, I will be 
93 years old and probably unable to walk. But I will go to Hong 
Kong even if I am in a wheelchair. I will be very happy even if 
I stay in Hong Kong for only a minute'." 
  In response to a Japanese reporter's question about Deng 
Xiaoping's everyday life, she said: "The secret of my father's 
longevity is living a regular life." She said Deng Xiaoping 
likes reading and subscribing to a dozen newspapers which he 
finishes everyday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2429 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi046_k_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deng's Daughter Visits Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0803145794 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1310 GMT 
8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0803145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo 8 Mar (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- Xiao Rong (aka 
Mao Mao 3029 3029,) author of the book My Father Deng 
Xiaoping, talked about her father's recent conditions and 
life when answering Japanese reporters' questions at a news 
conference on the occasion of the circulation of the book in 
question here today. 
  Xiao Rong said: The description of my father's conditions 
today can be boiled down to two sentences. The first is that he 
is not ill, and the second is that he is, after all, 90 years 
old. It is the law of nature; his physical quality, in its 
entirety, is poorer than it was a couple of years ago. 
Nevertheless, he persists in doing some exercises every day, 
mainly walking. He makes it a rule to walk three kilometers 
each day, even against Beijing's cold wind. 
  Xiao Rong said: I personally believe that a secret of my 
father's longevity is precisely an orderly life. Even before 
his retirement, when he was still in office, he led a very 
orderly life. Since his retirement, he has continued to maintain 
a very orderly life. Every day, he gets up at around 0700, then 
he does some exercises, in a workout with several movements, 
which he himself has worked out. After breakfast, he reads the 
press. My father just loves to read newspapers. I believe, in 
his mind, reading the press is no less important than reading 
documents. He subscribes to a dozen or so newspapers, which he 
invariably reads through -- the whole lot. We used to say as a 
joke that the source of information in our family is precisely 
my father because, none of us in our family reads the press as 
earnestly as he does, none of us reads such a huge volume as he 
does. Sometimes, he will ask us which team won a famous 
football match a day before, and none of us can say. Then he 
will be very pleased with himself, telling us the result. After 
reading the press, it is time for a walk in the morning. In the 
remainder of the day, he sometimes does some reading, or watches 
television. Then, there are his grandchildren. When they are 
back from school at noon, they invariably will go to see their 
grandpa and play with him. My father is a person who just loves 
the family, his children and grandchildren. Therefore, being 
together with his family members is his happiest time every day. 
He spends most of his time in the evening playing bridge. He 
has a few loyal partners playing bridge, most of whom are 
retired old men. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2430 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi046_k_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views Father's Health in Tokyo Interview </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803124994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1238 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 8 KYODO -- China's veteran leader Deng 
Xiaoping is healthy, but avoids making public appearances unless 
he feels his presence is necessary to encourage reforms, his 
youngest daughter Xiao Rong said in Tokyo on Tuesday [8 March]. 
  "His only aim of appearing in public is to encourage better 
(implementation of)... overall policies, to assist and help our 
current leaders in even better implementing the route of 
construction," Xiao said in an interview with KYODO NEWS SERVICE. 
  Xiao is in Tokyo to promote the Japanese edition of her book 
My Father, Deng Xiaoping, the first part of a 
biography of the 89-year old revolutionary covering the years up 
to 1949. 
  In one of his rare public appearances the frail-looking Deng 
was shown on television during the Chinese Lunar New Year 
Festival last month. 
  On these occasions Xiao is always seen at her father's side 
supporting him by the arm, whispering into his partially deaf 
ears and translating his almost incomprehensible utterings. 
  She laughingly dismissed allegations that her 
interpretations 
of his utterings reflected more her own opinion than her 
father's views, saying that was "incomprehension and ignorance." 
  "Wouldn't that be putting my father to a much too low 
level?" 
She said, adding that her father has no speech problems and 
often talks for 30 minutes at a time. 
  At a press conference earlier in the day, Xiao said, "at the 
moment (Deng) has no disease" and walks three-kilometers a day, 
even during Beijing's cold winter weather. 
  Xiao said that although her father is frail, he is usually 
amused by frequent foreign press reports that he is rumored to 
have cancer or has already died. 
  The secret of her father's longevity is his regular routine, 
she said. Deng wakes up at 7 A.M., reads the newspapers in the 
morning, enjoys playing with his grandchildren in the afternoon 
and plays bridge with old friends in the evening, she said. 
  Although he has given up all political posts, the mastermind 
of China's market reforms is still believed to have his say in 
major policy decisions. 
  Deng has complete confidence in the current leadership, said 
Xiao, indicating that he has entrusted day-to-day politics 
entirely to President Jiang Zemin, Prime Minister Li Peng and 
Vice Premier Zhu Rongji. 
  The three "actually come to see him very seldom," but still 
consult with the senior leader on important matters, she said. 
Yet Deng does not expect them to adopt his advice, which he 
wants to be understood as "his personal opinion," she said. 
  Xiao adamantly dismissed efforts in China to create a new 
personality cult around the father of China's socialist market 
economy. 
  She said the Deng family would agree to setting up a 
monument 
after her father's death, but oppose the construction of a 
pendant to Mao Zedong's mausoleum in Beijing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

