<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Eighth National People's Congress Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Spokesman's First News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903115994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1134 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 9 (XINHUA) -- Zhou Jue, spokesman 
for China's top legislature, answered questions about the NPC's 
[National People's Congress] legislative work, the Hong Kong 
issue and the law on protection of Taiwan investors at a press 
conference held in the Great Hall of the People this morning. 
  Asked about the law on the protection of investment by 
Taiwan 
compatriots which was promulgated by the National People's 
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee recently, Zhou, spokesman for 
the current session of the Eighth NPC, said that the law was 
designed to suit the current situation. He said that economic 
exchanges across the Taiwan straits and Taiwan investment in the 
Mainland have been increasing substantially. But there are 
still no direct transport and commercial links between the two 
sides of the straits. 
  Zhou said that the new law is formulated to ensure the 
personal safety and economic interests and rights of Taiwan 
investors to the Mainland and keep their enterprises on the 
Mainland from being requisitioned. This has fully demonstrated 
the Mainland's respect for the interests and rights of Taiwan 
investors and its sincerity in developing trade relations across 
the straits, he said. 
  Asked about possibility of an agreement on protection of 
investment by the two sides, Zhou said that Taiwan is an 
inseparable part of China and the relations between the Chinese 
Central Government and Taiwan are the relations between a 
central government and a locality. 
  "It is out of the question that the two sides may sign any 
agreement," he said. 
  In response to a question about whether Hong Kong's 
three-tier political structure will be terminated when China 
resumes sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997, the spokesman blamed 
the uncooperative attitude of the British side for the breakdown 
of Sino-British talks on the Hong Kong issue. 
  Zhou pointed out that the three-tier political structure of 
Hong Kong will be terminated by June 30, 1997, the date set in 
the Sino- British joint declaration. 
  Asked about NPC accelerating the pace of legislation and 
strengthening legislative supervision, he said that the NPC and 
its standing committee has accelerated legislation, especially 
in the economic field, in the past year. It passed 22 laws in 
1993, including 12 economic laws, setting a record in NPC 
history. 
  He said that last year the NPC Standing Committee sent ten 
inspection teams to 15 provinces and autonomous regions to 
oversee the implementation of the laws, and learned opinions of 
relevant departments on key tasks of the government and the 
issues that people are concerned about. 
  The spokesman said that the Eighth NPC will strive to 
promulgate 152 laws during its term of service, which will end 
in 1998. The laws will form the framework of the legal system 
of the socialist market economy and perfect legislation in other 
areas. 
  At the press conference attended by several hundred 
correspondents from China and abroad, Zhou also answered 
questions about Sino-U.S. relations, reform of large- and 
medium-sized state- owned enterprises and the securities law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

