<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Eighth National People's Congress Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Sources' Quoted on Li Peng Report </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903112294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1059 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 9 KYODO -- The Second Session of 
China's Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) will open its 
two-week meeting Thursday [10 March] with delegates expected to 
debate the main issues of the country's ongoing economic reform. 
  Premier Li Peng will open the annual session with a reading 
of his government work report which will lay down the themes of 
the congress and the government's main tasks for this year. 
  Li is expected to call for 9 percent economic growth this 
year and an inflation rate below 10 percent, while he will push 
forward reforms in the banking, financial and tax sectors, 
Chinese sources said. 
  Much of Li's report is based on the decision by the Third 
Plenum of the 14th Communist Party Congress last October to 
construct a "socialist market economy," sources said. 
  The report is expected to address China's main economic 
problems including inflation, high fixed asset investment and an 
inefficient state sector, as well as other problems including 
corruption and excessive bureaucracy. 
  Not much new is expected in the report, although Li will 
announce new regulations on fixed assets investment and the 
establishment of a state development bank to stabilize the 
funding of basic construction projects, well-placed sources said. 
  Li will also announce a plan for reappropriating funds 
raised 
by state-run enterprises for infrastructure projects to help pay 
for the bankruptcy of inefficient enterprises and displaced 
workers, the sources said. 
  The report will briefly praise the work done in 1993 in 
nearly every area of government including, propaganda, science 
and technology, culture, health and education, while laying down 
the work outline in these areas for 1994. 
  Li will stress that continued economic development will need 
a stable social environment and call on all levels of government 
to safeguard social order and fight corruption in government. 
  On foreign policy, the premier is not expected to harshly 
criticize the British handling of issues concerning Hong Kong, 
but in a veiled reference to the U.S. he will staunchly 
maintain that China will refuse to accept any form of hegemony 
or power politics, sources said. 
  On Friday, Chen Jinhua will give his report on the 
implementation of national economic and social development and 
submit his draft plan for 1994, while Finance Minister Li 
Zhongli will report on the 1993 and 1994 state budgets. 
  During the congress, the 2,970 deputies will later debate, 
amend and approve the reports along with reports from the 
Supreme People's Court, the Supreme People's Procurator and the 
NPC Standing Committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

