<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Eighth National People's Congress Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputies Arrive in Beijing </H4>
<F P=102> OW0803091594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0840 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 8 (XINHUA) -- Nearly 3,000 deputies 
to the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) have arrived in 
Beijing by this afternoon to attend its second session due to 
start Thursday (March 10). 
  The annual NPC session is an important event in China's 
political and economic life. During the coming session, 
deputies will deliberate Premier Li Peng's government work 
report, the national economic development plan, the state 
budget, and work reports of the Supreme People's Court, Supreme 
People's Procuratorate and the NPC Standing Committee. 
  This year's NPC session comes about 10 days earlier than 
usual, and future sessions are expected to be convened still 
earlier in the year. Observers say this is to ensure better 
planning of government work for the whole year. 
  Deputies know what business they will be doing during the 
session. In the past year most of them have made extensive 
investigations in their respective constituencies. Upon their 
arrival in Beijing, they start reading documents, preparing 
motions and exchanging information with one another. 
  Punco, a Tibetan deputy from Monba, an ethnic minority in 
China with the smallest population, said participation in state 
affairs was beyond the dream of Monba people in the past. 
Though the "gexia" (parliament) of old Tibet held meetings 
every year, it had nothing to do with Tibetan serfs. 
  Punco said he plans to raise a motion on developing Tibetan 
economy, especially its agriculture and animal husbandry. 
  Wang Dazhong, a deputy from a big state enterprise in 
Shaanxi 
Province, said that, as the country is probing ways for the 
establishment of a modern enterprise system in 1994, he plans to 
express his opinions on the necessity of establishing standards 
for market behaviors and strengthening law enforcement. 
  The Eighth NPC has 2,978 deputies. In the past year, five 
deputies passed away, one resigned, and two were disqualified. 
Standing committees of local people's congresses elected 
deputies for the vacancies according to law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-2446 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi046_k_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-046 </AU>
