<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on CPPCC Session Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803130994 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0903 
GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0803130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 8 Mar (XINHUA) -- The Second Session of 
the Eighth Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference 
[CPPCC] National Committee opened at the Great Hall of the 
People this afternoon. 
  Li Ruihuan, chairman of the CPPCC National Committee, 
presided over the opening. He declared that of the total 2,097 
members of the CPPCC National Committee, 1,917 had already 
report to the session and 1,860 were attending the opening, thus 
fulfilling the quorum. 
  Vice chairmen of the CPPCC National Committee who were 
seated 
in the front row of the rostrum were Ye Xuanping, Wu Xueqian, 
Yang Rudai, Wang Zhaoguo, Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme, Seypidin Aze, 
Hong Xuezhi, Zhao Puchu, Qian Weichang, Hu Sheng, Qian 
Zhengying, Su Buqing, Ding Guangxun, Dong Yinchu, Sun Fuling, 
Ann Tse-kai, Henry Fok Ying-tung, and Ma Man-kai. 
  Party and state leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Zhu 
Rongji, Liu Huaqing, Hu Jintao, and Rong Yiren were seated on 
the rostrum. They offered congratulations on the opening of the 
session. 
  At 1500 [0700 GMT], Chairman Li Ruihuan declared the session 
open. As all member stood at attention, a military band played 
the national anthem. 
  The session first examined and adopted an agenda for the 
current session of the CPPCC National Committee. According to 
the agenda, members of the CPPCC National Committee will: 
examine a work report of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC 
National Committee; attend the Second Session of the Eighth 
National People's Congress as nonvoting delegates; deliberate 
and approve the "CPPCC Constitution (amended);" deliberate and 
approve a report by the Motions Committee of the Eighth CPPCC 
National Committee on examining motions having been submitted to 
the Second Session of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee; 
deliberate and approve various resolutions to be adopted by the 
Second Session of the Eighth National People's Congress; and 
elect new vice-chairmen, Standing Committee members, and 
secretary- general of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee. 
  Entrusted by the Standing Committee of the CPPCC National 
Committee, Ye Xuanping, vice chairman of the CPPCC National 
Committee, delivered a report on the work of the Standing 
Committee. In the report, the vice chairman first reviewed the 
work of the Standing Committee over the past year. He said: 
Since the First Session of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee, 
the Standing Committee, guided by Comrade Deng Xiaoping's theory 
of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, has worked 
hard to explore new ways to engage in political consultation and 
exercise democratic supervision, paying attention to selecting 
issues, bringing into play the favorable factors, and ensuring 
effective participation in the administration and discussion of 
state affairs focused on the central task of the nation. The 
Standing Committee has given full play to the role of the 
special committees and organized members to take part in various 
activities on a regular basis; has stepped up information 
service and reflected popular feelings in a timely and accurate 
manner; and has actively conducted CPPCC's exchanges with 
foreign countries in line with the overall arrangements of 
national diplomacy; thereby making advances in all fields of 
endeavor. 
  He said: The party and the government have already decided 
on the basic policy for 1994, a year of vital importance to 
China's reform, opening up, and socialist modernization drive. 
This year will be the second year for the Eighth CPPCC National 
Committee to carry out its work. The main points of the 
Standing Committee's work are: studying in depth the theory of 
building socialism with Chinese characteristics to continuously 
raise the consensus; selecting major topics in economic 
construction, reform and opening up, spiritual civilization 
construction, and the people's life for investigation and study 
to ensure effective participation in the administration and 
discussion of state affairs; carrying forward the fine tradition 
and bringing into play the role of the democratic parties and 
the people's mass organizations in participating in the 
administration and discussion of state affairs; forging close 
ties with the people of all nationalities and in various 
circles, and harmonizing their relations and transmitting 
viewpoints of higher authorities to lower levels to safeguard 
political and social stability; improving and strengthening 
inspection and the work of handling motions to promote 
democratic supervision; broadening channels of communication 
with overseas Chinese to promote the motherland's peaceful 
reunification; utilizing the CPPCC's advantages to continue to 
develop friendly exchanges with parliaments and nongovernmental 
organizations of other countries; and improving the performance 
of offices in an all-round way by raising the quality of 
officers and raising office work efficiency. 
  Ye Xuanping's report received thunderous applause from 
members. 
  The "CPPCC Constitution (amended)" was submitted to members 
for deliberation at the meeting today. 
  Leading comrades who were seated on the rostrum were also 
Tian Jiyun, Li Lanqing, Li Tieying, Yang Baibing, Zou Jiahua, 
Jiang Chunyun, Qian Qichen, Wei Jianxing, Wen Jiabao, Wang 
Hanbin, Zhang Zhen, Ren Jianxin, Ni Zhifu, Chen Muhua, Sun 
Qimeng, Lei Jieqiong, Li Ximing, Wang Bingqian, Wang Guangying, 
Cheng Siyuan, Lu Jiaxi, Buhe, Tomur Dawamat, Li Peiyao, Wu 
Jieping, Chi Haotian, Song Jian, Li Guixian, Chen Junsheng, 
Ismail Amat, Pen Peiyuan, Luo Gan, and Zhang Siqing. 
  After the meeting today, Chairman Li Ruihu and Vice Chairmen 
Ye Xuanping, Wu Xueqian, Yang Rudai, and Wang Zhaoguo met with 
new members of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee, who had been 
elected through by-elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

