<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes History </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703100694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0845 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Backgrounder: Chinese People's Political Consultative </F>
Conference" -- XINHUA headline] 
  [Text] Beijing, March 7 (XINHUA) -- The Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) is an intensive 
patriotic united front organization established on the eve of 
the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949. It was 
founded jointly by the Communist Party of China (CPC), 
democratic parties, individuals without party affiliation, 
people's organizations, and personages from various social 
circles. 
  The first plenary session of the CPPCC was held in Beijing 
between September 21 and 30, 1949 and attended by 662 
representatives from all sections of the Chinese society. At 
the time, CPPCC exercised the functions and powers of the 
later-formed National People's Congress (NPC), China's 
legislature. The first CPPCC session adopted the "Common 
Program of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference," proclaiming the founding of the People's Republic 
of China (PRC), and elected the committee of the central 
people's government of the PRC with Mao Zedong as its chairman. 
It also decided the national flag and anthem, elected the first 
180-member National Committee of the CPPCC. 
  The Second CPPCC National Committee convened its first 
plenary session in Beijing in December, 1954. It declared that 
because of the convention of the First National People's 
Congress (NPC), CPPCC ceased to function as the country's 
legislature, but continued to exist as an organization of the 
People's Democratic United Front. 
  The plenary session elected Mao Zedong honorary chairman and 
Zhou Enlai chairman of its national committee. The Second 
National Committee of the CPPCC held three plenary sessions. 
  The Third CPPCC National Committee held its first plenary 
session in Beijing in April, 1959. From this session on, CPPCC 
members have begun to attend NPC sessions without voting rights. 
The session elected Mao Zedong honorary chairman and Zhou Enlai 
chairman of the National Committee. The Third CPPCC National 
Committee held four plenary sessions. 
  The first plenary session of the Fourth CPPCC National 
Committee was held in Beijing between December 1964 and January 
1965. It re- elected Mao Zedong and Zhou Enlai its honorary 
chairman and chairman respectively. CPPCC was forced to stop 
operation during the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) and, as a 
result, the Fourth CPPCC National Committee held only one 
plenary session. 
  The Fifth CPPCC National Committee convened its first 
plenary 
session in Beijing in February 1976. Deng Xiaoping was elected 
its chairman. The National Committee held five plenary sessions. 
  The Sixth CPPCC National Committee, which convened its first 
plenary session in Beijing in June 1983, elected Deng Yingchao 
its chairwoman. The National Committee held five plenary 
sessions. 
  The Seventh CPPCC National Committee, which held its first 
plenary in Beijing between March 24 and April 10 of 1988, 
elected Li Xiannian its chairman. The National Committee 
convened five plenary sessions altogether. 
  The Eighth CPPCC National Committee held its first plenary 
session in Beijing during March 14-27, 1993. Attended by 2,093 
members, it elected Li Ruihuan its chairman. 
  CPPCC has always been an organization for patriotic united 
front work under the leadership of CPC. It consists of members 
of CPC and eight democratic parties, democratic personages 
without party affiliation, members of people's organizations, 
representatives of minority nationalities, prominent figures 
from all walks of life, representatives of Taiwan, Hong Kong and 
Macao compatriots and returned overseas Chinese, and specially 
invited people. 
  CPPCC is an important instrument for promoting socialist 
democracy in China's political life. It participates in 
political consultations on major state policies and important 
issues concerning people's life, and exercises democratic 
supervision over CPC and the government by making suggestions 
and criticisms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

