<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC Spokesman Views Expectations of Second Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703123294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1205 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 7 (XINHUA) -- The coming session of 
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) is expected to give a boost to 
China's modernization drive and socialist democratic politics, 
according to a CPPCC spokesman. 
  Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, Li Luye, the 
spokesman, said that the second session of the CPPCC Eighth 
National Committee to be opened tomorrow will be convened at a 
time when the country witnesses a robust economic development, 
political stability, unity of all nationalities and social 
progress. 
  Reviewing the work of the National Committee over the past 
year, Li said that CPPCC has played an important role in 
promoting exchanges across the Taiwan Straits, steps toward the 
reunification of China. 
  Answering a question on the ongoing anti-corruption drive in 
China, Li said that CPPCC has spared no effort to support and 
participate in the anticorruption drive launched by the Central 
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State 
Council. 
  Members of the CPPCC National Committee formed six groups, 
which conducted corruption-related investigations together with 
relevant departments of the State Council, the spokesman said. 
  Zhao Weizhi, deputy secretary-general of the National 
Committee, answered a question about revision of the CPPCC 
Constitution. Revision of the existing Constitution, which was 
adopted in 1982, is being guided by the spirit of the 14th 
National Congress of the Communist Party of China and aims at 
its convergence with the amended Constitution of the People's 
Republic of China, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

