<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Speaks at `Gathering' Marking Womens Day </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503151894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1405 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0503151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 5 (XINHUA) -- More than 10,000 
Chinese and foreign women gathered in Beijing today to mark the 
84th anniversary of March 8 -- International Women's Day. 
  The gathering also aimed to greet the World Women's Congress 
which is to be held in Beijing in 1995. 
  Chinese Premier Li Peng attended the gathering, which was 
presided over by Chen Muhua, vice-chairman of the Standing 
Committee of the National People's Congress and president of the 
All-China Women's Federation. 
  Speaking to the gathering, Li Peng expressed regards to 
Chinese women of all nationalities, of Taiwan, Hong Kong and 
Macao compatriots on behalf of the Central Committee of the 
Chinese Communist Party (CPC) and the State Council. 
  He said that Chinese women constitute a great force for 
China's reforms and opening up and modernization. 
  Since China adopted economic reforms and opened to the 
outside world, there have been great changes in Chinese women's 
outlook, with remarkable progress in the quality of the women. 
  He said that Chinese women were actively taking part in 
economic development and had made important contributions in 
political, cultural and social sectors. 
  He noted that Chinese women enjoy a high status in society 
and they really hold up half the sky in building socialism with 
Chinese characteristics. 
  In 1995, the United Nations will hold the Fourth World 
Women's Congress in Beijing. Li Peng said that the congress is 
an important meeting to study women's issues of the world. 
  He said that it is a great honor for China to have the 
opportunity to prepare for and host the congress. 
  He said that the Chinese Government, Chinese people, and 
Chinese women will go all out to prepare for the congress, and 
will ensure its success. 
  The premier noted that now China is at an important 
development period. It is the common will of all Chinese 
people, including Chinese women, to turn China into a modern and 
socialist country based on prosperity, democracy and 
civilization. 
  He said that China's future is bright and the world future 
is 
broad. 
  Other party and government leaders, including Hu Jintao and 
Rong Yiren, attended the gathering. 
  Some foreign guests also attended the gathering. 
  Before his speech, Premier Li Peng and other leaders met a 
group of outstanding women who have been giving reports of their 
achievements in different parts of the country. 

</TEXT>

