<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Small Towns Develop by `Leaps and Bounds' Under Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503163594 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0814 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0503163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Jia Fenyong (6328 1164 0516)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 18 Feb (XINHUA) -- According to 
information gathered by this reporter from a national forum on 
the development of small towns held by the Ministry of Civil 
Affairs today, the development of small towns in our country has 
proceeded by leaps and bounds since the program of reform and 
opening up was initiated. By the end of 1992, there were 55,000 
small towns in rural China, of which 14,500 were organized along 
administrative lines, compared with 2,200 in the early eighties. 
  Comrades attending the forum were of the opinion that the 
development of small towns is an inevitable consequence and 
objective demand of rural reform, as well as the inevitable 
direction in which urbanization with Chinese characteristics 
must proceed. The proliferation of small towns has resulted in 
the transfer of large numbers of surplus workers in rural China 
to secondary and tertiary industries, thereby promoting an 
industrial restructuring within the farming sector. The 
development of small towns has stimulated the exchange of 
commodities in rural areas, promoted market development, and 
facilitated the formation of socialized service networks in the 
countryside. Moreover, the urbanization mode adopted for the 
development of small towns, in which "people leave their 
farmland but not their hometowns," has substantially bucked the 
tide of migrants from rural areas into large and medium cities 
in the course of modernization. 
  The Ministry of Civil Affairs held the forum with the aim of 
further implementing the important strategic ideas of the party 
Central Committee and the State Council regarding small towns, 
and of making preparations for revising the standards for 
administratively organized towns to facilitate the process of 
integrating urban and rural areas. In his speech, Minister of 
Civil Affairs Doje Cering pointed out: During the current 
development of small towns, we must ensure that the geographical 
distribution of such towns is rational and achieve better 
results by virtue of the proper size of such towns. Also, we 
should establish a multilevel and multifunctional social 
security system, bearing the distinctive features of small towns 
in mind, so as to gradually advance the process of introducing 
community-wide social security in small towns. 
  More than 30 people attended today's forum. They included 
specialists from the Geography Institute of the Chinese Academy 
of Sciences, the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, the Chinese 
Urban Planning Research Institute, Beijing University, and other 
research institutes and educational institutions, as well as 
comrades in charge of relevant State Council departments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

