<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators Propose Passing Law on Taiwan Investments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303150494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1415 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 3 (XINHUA) -- China's lawmakers 
today called for the legislature to pass a draft law on the 
protection of investments of Taiwan compatriots. 
  The revised version of the draft law is ready to be 
promulgated, said members of the Standing Committee of the 
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) at its Sixth Session, 
which started on Tuesday. 
  They suggested that it be passed during this session, which 
ends this Saturday [5 March]. 
  To safeguard the interests of investors from Taiwan by law 
will be conducive to encourage more companies, enterprises, 
organizations or individuals there to invest in China's 
mainland, said Li Yining, vice-chairman of the NPC Law Committee. 
  "It has been aimed to further promote the economic exchanges 
across the Taiwan Straits," said Li, who is a renowned economist 
in China. 
  The draft law stipulates that the state will not nationalize 
or requisition the investments; but under special circumstances 
and for the need of the public good, the state could purchase 
the investments through legal procedures, with the investors 
being reimbursed. 
  Two vice-chairmen of the NPC Standing Committee, Ni Zhifu 
and 
Li Peiyao, said the draft law should make it clear that the 
Taiwan investors should observe China's laws just as they will 
be protected by the law. 
  The draft law on the protection of investments of Taiwan 
compatriots was submitted to the legislature for deliberation 
for the first time on December 10 last year. 
  It was submitted to the lawmakers for another review 
yesterday after being revised according to opinions both from 
the members of the NPC Standing Committee and feedback from the 
NPC Finance Committee, localities and departments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

